2. Biochemical Aspects of Heavy Metals (Hg, Cd, Pb, Cr)
Heavy metals are metallic elements with high density (> 5 g/cm³) and atomic number, many of which are toxic
even at low concentrations. They are persistent (cannot be degraded), accumulate in organisms, and interfere
with biochemical processes by binding to sulphydryl (–SH) groups, displacing essential metals, or generating
free radicals.
2.1 Mercury (Hg)
Mercury – The Methylation Menace
Sources: Coal combustion (largest global source ~40%); gold mining (artisanal); chlor-alkali plants;
thermometers/fluorescent lamps; volcanic emissions
Chemical forms and toxicity:
• Elemental Hg (Hgn): vapour; inhaled ® CNS; less toxic by ingestion (poorly absorbed)
• Inorganic Hg²n (mercuric): skin/GI damage; kidney damage; less able to cross BBB
• Methylmercury (CHnHgn): MOST TOXIC; lipid soluble; crosses blood-brain barrier AND placenta;
bioaccumulates in fish; neurotoxin
Methylation: Sulphate-reducing bacteria (Desulfovibrio) in anaerobic sediments methylate Hg²n ®
CHnHgn
Mechanism: CHnHgn binds –SH groups on enzymes and proteins ® disrupts neurological function; inhibits
tubulin (cell division); teratogen
Minamata Disease (Japan, 1956): Chisso Corporation dumped Hg into Minamata Bay ® bioaccumulated in fish ®
2,000+ deaths; 10,000+ affected; neurological damage
WHO limit in fish: 0.5 mg/kg (0.1 mg/kg for methylmercury)
2.2 Cadmium (Cd)
Cadmium – The Kidney Destroyer
Sources: Zinc smelting (Cd is a by-product); phosphate fertilisers; Ni-Cd batteries; cigarette smoke
(smokers have 2–4× higher Cd); plastics/pigments
Speciation: Cd²n is the main toxic form; highly mobile at low pH
Mechanism of toxicity:
• Mimics Ca²n and Zn²n ® enters cells via Ca channels; displaces Zn²n from enzymes
• Accumulates in kidneys (half-life 10–30 years in body!)
• Induces metallothionein (MT) protein synthesis in liver ® MT-Cd complex transported to kidney ® MT
degrades ® free Cd²n damages renal tubules
