2.3 Lead (Pb)
Lead – The Children's Neurotoxin
Sources: Leaded petrol (phased out globally but legacy soil Pb remains); lead-based paint; smelting;
water pipes; ammunition; batteries; traditional cosmetics (sindoor, kajal)
Speciation: Pb²n dominant; organic Pb (tetraethyl lead TEL, tetramethyl lead TML) were fuel additives
Mechanism of toxicity:
• Pb²n mimics Ca²n ® enters neurons; disrupts neurotransmission
• Inhibits haem synthesis (d-ALAD enzyme ® proto/coproporphyrin in urine = biomarker)
• Anaemia: Pb inhibits haem synthesis + increases RBC fragility
• Stored in bone (t½ ~25 years) – re-mobilised during pregnancy, osteoporosis
• Children most vulnerable: IQ reduction (each 10 μg/dL blood Pb = 2–4 IQ points lost)
• "Saturnism" = chronic Pb poisoning; Burton's line (blue-black gum line)
Blood Pb standard: WHO reference value = 5 μg/dL (no safe level for children); Air NAAQS: 0.5 μg/m³ (annual)
2.4 Chromium (Cr)
Chromium – The Speciation Story
Sources: Leather tanning (largest Cr source in India); electroplating; stainless steel; pigments; chromate
salts
The two faces of Chromium:
• Cr³n (trivalent): ESSENTIAL micronutrient (glucose tolerance factor); low toxicity; insoluble at neutral pH;
NOT a carcinogen
• Crnn (hexavalent – chromate CrOn²n, dichromate CrnOn²n): CARCINOGEN (IARC Group 1); soluble;
mobile; easily absorbed
Mechanism of Crnn toxicity:
