3. Metalloids: Arsenic (As) and Selenium (Se)
Metalloids have properties intermediate between metals and non-metals. Arsenic and selenium are
environmentally critical because they occur naturally at toxic concentrations in groundwater of many regions, and
their toxicity is highly dependent on chemical speciation.
3.1 Arsenic (As)
Parameter Details
Atomic number 33; Group 15 (pnictogen); metalloid
Sources Geogenic (natural rock weathering; primary); coal combustion; copper smelting; wood preservatives
(CCA); pesticides (lead arsenate); herbicides
Speciation As³n (arsenite: HnAsOn, HnAsOnn) = more toxic, more soluble, mobile in reducing conditions
Asnn (arsenate: HnAsOnn, HAsOn²n) = less toxic, adsorbed to Fe oxides in oxic conditions
Organic: MMA (monomethylarsonic), DMA (dimethylarsinic) = LEAST toxic (methylation =
detoxification)
Mechanism of
toxicity
As³n: binds –SH groups ® inhibits pyruvate dehydrogenase, a-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase ®
disrupts Krebs cycle; ATP depletion Asnn: uncouples oxidative phosphorylation (replaces phosphate
in ATP synthesis ® unstable As-ADP)
Target organs Skin, liver, kidney, lung, bladder, nervous system
Health effects Arsenicosis: keratosis (skin hardening), hyperpigmentation, Mees lines on nails Cancers: IARC Group
1: skin, lung, bladder, kidney cancer Vascular effects: Blackfoot disease (Taiwan; peripheral vascular
disease)
Indian crisis West Bengal + Bangladesh: 70+ million people exposed to As > 50 μg/L in groundwater Mechanism:
reducing groundwater ® reductive dissolution of FeOOH ® As³n released
Standard WHO: 10 μg/L; BIS 10500: 10 μg/L (previously 50 μg/L)
3.2 Selenium (Se)
Parameter Details
Atomic number 34; Group 16 (chalcogen); metalloid
Sources Coal combustion fly ash; agricultural drainage from Se-rich soils; glass manufacturing; animal feed (Se
supplementation)
Speciation Senn (selenate SeOn²n): oxidising conditions; mobile; plant-available Senn (selenite SeOn²n): less
mobile; adsorbed; reducing conditions Se²n (selenide): reducing; forms metal selenides; insoluble
Organic Se (selenomethionine, selenocysteine): incorporated into proteins
Dual role ESSENTIAL at low concentrations (0.04–0.1 mg/kg diet): component of glutathione peroxidase
(antioxidant); thyroid hormone metabolism; immune function TOXIC at high concentrations (> 0.5
mg/kg diet): narrow therapeutic window
Deficiency disease Keshan disease (cardiomyopathy; China); Kashin-Beck disease (osteoarthropathy; China/Tibet)
Toxicity effects Selenosis: hair loss, nail deformity, garlic breath (dimethylselenide), neurological symptoms
Teratogenic to birds (deformed embryos; Kesterson Reservoir, California – selenium drainage crisis)
