4. CO, Tropospheric On, PAN and VOCs
4.1 Carbon Monoxide (CO)
Carbon Monoxide – The Silent Killer
Sources: Incomplete combustion of fossil fuels (vehicles = 80% urban CO); biomass burning; cigarette
smoke; indoor cookstoves (major indoor air pollutant in India)
Formation: C + ½On ® CO (incomplete; oxygen-deficient combustion)
Mechanism of toxicity:
CO binds haemoglobin with 200–250× GREATER AFFINITY than On
Hb + CO ® COHb (carboxyhaemoglobin) ® cannot carry On ® tissue hypoxia
Also binds myoglobin (muscle) and cytochrome c oxidase (mitochondria) ® impairs cellular respiration
COHb also shifts On dissociation curve LEFT (Haldane effect) ® reduced On release from remaining
OxyHb
Symptoms by % COHb: <20% = headache, fatigue; 20–40% = confusion, vomiting; 40–60% = convulsions;
>60% = fatal
Treatment: 100% On (displaces CO from Hb); hyperbaric On for severe cases
NAAQS India: 4.0 mg/m³ (8-hr average); WHO: 10 mg/m³ (8-hr)
4.2 Tropospheric Ozone (On)
Tropospheric ozone is a secondary pollutant formed by photochemical reactions of NOx and VOCs in sunlight.
Unlike stratospheric On (beneficial UV shield), ground-level On is a powerful oxidant harmful to health,
vegetation, and materials.
