4.3 PAN (Peroxyacyl Nitrate)
PAN – Structure, Formation and Effects
Full name: Peroxyacetyl Nitrate (PAN); formula: CHnC(O)OnNOn
Formation: From oxidation of VOCs (especially acetaldehyde, acetone) by OH• ® peroxyacetyl radical +
NOn:
CHnCHO + OH• ® CHnC(O)• + HnO ® CHnC(O)On• + On ® CHnC(O)On• + NOn n PAN
Thermally unstable: Decomposes at > 25°C ® releases NOn (acts as NOx reservoir for long-range
transport)
Stable at low T: Can travel thousands of km at high altitude ® deposits NOx in remote areas
Health effects: Potent lachrymator (eye irritant at 1–2 ppb); respiratory irritant; mutagenic (alkylating
agent)
Phytotoxicity: Most phytotoxic compound in smog; damages chloroplasts; causes "glazing" and
"bronzing" of leaves at < 20 ppb (sensitive plants)
PAN family: PAN (most studied), PPN (peroxypropionic nitrate), PBN (peroxybutyryl nitrate)
