5. Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs)
Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs) are organic chemicals that are resistant to environmental degradation,
accumulate in living organisms, and pose risks to human health and the environment. They share four key
properties captured in the "4-P" framework: Persistence, Partitioning, Potency, Pathways.
5.1 Four Properties of POPs
The 4 Key Characteristics of POPs
1. Persistence: Half-life > 2 months in water, > 6 months in soil/sediment. Resist photolysis, hydrolysis,
biodegradation. Example: DDT half-life in soil = 10–15 years.
2. Bioaccumulation: Log Kow (octanol-water partition coefficient) > 5 ® highly lipophilic ® accumulate in
fatty tissues. BCF (bioconcentration factor) > 5000.
3. Toxicity: Cause adverse effects at very low concentrations (ng/kg to μg/kg): carcinogenicity, endocrine
disruption, reproductive toxicity, immunotoxicity, neurotoxicity.
4. Long-range transport: Volatile enough to evaporate from tropical regions ® condense in cold polar
regions ("grasshopper effect" / global distillation). Found in Arctic despite never being used there.
5.2 Stockholm Convention (2001) – Regulating POPs
The Stockholm Convention on POPs was adopted in 2001 and entered into force in 2004. India ratified in
2006. It lists POPs in three annexes:
