7. UGC NET Pattern MCQs with Explanations
Q1. Which class of pesticides acts by IRREVERSIBLY inhibiting acetylcholinesterase (AChE)?
(a) Organochlorines
(b) Pyrethroids
(c) Organophosphates
(d) Carbamates
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: Organophosphates (e.g., parathion, malathion, chlorpyrifos) irreversibly phosphorylate the serine
residue of AChE ® cannot break down acetylcholine ® cholinergic crisis. Carbamates also inhibit AChE but
REVERSIBLY. OCs affect Na channels. Pyrethroids keep Na channels open.
Q2. The Minamata disease was caused by contamination of the food chain with:
(a) Lead (Pb) from battery smelting
(b) Cadmium (Cd) from zinc mining drainage
(c) Methylmercury (CHnHgn) from industrial discharge
(d) Arsenic (As) from groundwater
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: Minamata disease (Japan, 1956): Chisso Corporation discharged inorganic Hg into Minamata Bay.
Sulphate-reducing bacteria methylated Hg²n ® CHnHgn ® bioaccumulated in fish ® humans. Symptoms: ataxia,
sensory loss, deafness, blindness, congenital Minamata (cerebral palsy-like). Named after Minamata city in
Kumamoto, Japan.
Q3. Carbon monoxide (CO) is toxic because it:
(a) Reacts with haemoglobin forming methaemoglobin
(b) Binds haemoglobin with 200–250× greater affinity than On forming COHb
(c) Inhibits acetylcholinesterase in the brain
(d) Generates reactive oxygen species in blood cells
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: CO binds haemoglobin at the same site as On but with 200–250 times greater affinity ® forms
carboxyhaemoglobin (COHb) ® On cannot bind ® tissue hypoxia. Additionally, COHb shifts the On-Hb dissociation
curve left (Haldane effect), making remaining OxyHb give up On less readily. Treatment: 100% On or hyperbaric
On.
Q4. PAN (Peroxyacetyl Nitrate) in photochemical smog acts as a NOx reservoir because:
(a) It stores NOx permanently, preventing smog formation
(b) It is thermally unstable at high temperatures and decomposes to release NOn
(c) It absorbs NOx from the atmosphere at all temperatures
(d) It reacts with water to form nitric acid
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: PAN n CHnC(O)On• + NOn (equilibrium; reversible). At > 25°C, PAN decomposes releasing NOn. At
cold high altitudes, PAN is stable ® transported thousands of km ® warms and decomposes ® deposits NOx in
remote areas far from the original emission source. This is why rural/arctic On levels are elevated by urban NOx
transported as PAN.
Q5. Which of the following POPs is classified under Annex B of the Stockholm Convention (restriction
rather than complete elimination)?
